### 11. Optimized Load Ordering

For the AX45MPV pipeline, interleave loads to maximize memory-level parallelism and hide latency. The ideal ordering loads pixels first (since they are reused across weight rows), then alternates weight loads with vd4dots to overlap compute with load:

```
vle8 v16, (ptr_b0)     # pixel 0 -- start loading early
vle8 v18, (ptr_b1)     # pixel 1
vle8 v20, (ptr_a0)     # weight ch0
vd4dots v0,  v20, v16  # ch0*pix0 (weight ch0 ready)
vd4dots v2,  v20, v18  # ch0*pix1
vle8 v22, (ptr_a1)     # weight ch1 (overlap with vd4dots)
vd4dots v4,  v22, v16  # ch1*pix0
vd4dots v6,  v22, v18  # ch1*pix1
vle8 v24, (ptr_a2)     # weight ch2
vd4dots v8,  v24, v16  # ch2*pix0
vd4dots v10, v24, v18  # ch2*pix1
vle8 v26, (ptr_a3)     # weight ch3
vd4dots v12, v26, v16  # ch3*pix0
vd4dots v14, v26, v18  # ch3*pix1
```

This interleaved pattern allows the load of the next weight row to overlap with vd4dots execution on the previous weight row. The 2 pixel loads are hoisted to the top since they are needed for all 8 vd4dots operations. Whether the compiler respects this ordering through inline asm depends on how the macros are structured -- since each macro is a separate asm statement with volatile, the compiler should preserve ordering.

